document.value: The death toll from a bomb attack on a mosque in the southern Indian city of Hyderabad and subsequent clashes between police and Muslim protesters has risen to 14, police said Saturday. A 10th victim died overnight from injuries sustained in Friday's blast at the 17th century Mecca Mosque, while police confirmed that four others had been killed in the ensuing violent protests. "The deaths are 14. Ten in the blast and four in the firing," said city police commissioner Balwinder Singh. More than 50 people were injured in the blast and subsequent melee, two of them seriously, Singh said. An improvised explosive device blew up near an area where 1,000 worshippers were reciting Friday prayers, said officials in Hyderabad, one of India's most developed cities and the capital of Andhra Pradesh state. India went on high security alert late Friday to avert possible sectarian violence between Muslims and Hindus, a home ministry spokesman said.
document.headline: 14 dead in India mosque blast, protests
